1
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:08,339
It's one thing to lead a team on the right path to winning a premiership

2
00:00:08,339 --> 00:00:11,519
or building a workplace that encourages growth and sustainability.

3
00:00:12,140 --> 00:00:14,300
But what if your team is an entire city?

4
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:18,000
How do you generate a positive environment for over 6 million people?

5
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:21,980
G'day, it's Luke Darson.

6
00:00:22,260 --> 00:00:24,480
The idea of self-improvement and leadership,

7
00:00:24,899 --> 00:00:27,640
both on and off the field, has been a lifelong passion of mine.

8
00:00:28,339 --> 00:00:30,539
With one of my oldest friends, we created a leader collective

9
00:00:30,539 --> 00:00:33,280
and have had the privilege of working with thousands of leaders

10
00:00:33,280 --> 00:00:36,460
in education, sport, industry and the arts

11
00:00:36,460 --> 00:00:40,420
that have helped shift to what we see as the 21st century style of leadership

12
00:00:40,420 --> 00:00:41,880
where everyone has a voice.

13
00:00:42,880 --> 00:00:46,460
In this podcast, we hear stories from these iconic leaders.

14
00:00:47,000 --> 00:01:05,019
I was lucky to be joined by the Lord Mayor of Melbourne, Sally Capp.

15
00:01:05,500 --> 00:01:09,260
Leadership is something that she does on a daily basis on a pretty grand scale

16
00:01:09,260 --> 00:01:11,980
and we discuss the importance of valuing input from others

17
00:01:11,980 --> 00:01:13,760
and being able to embrace your failures.

18
00:01:14,920 --> 00:01:18,200
Well, this is always an honour and a great privilege to sit down

19
00:01:18,200 --> 00:01:21,379
with the Lord Mayor of Melbourne and an inspiration in every sense.

20
00:01:21,719 --> 00:01:23,200
Sally Capp, thanks for joining me today, Sal.

21
00:01:23,459 --> 00:01:24,359
Thank you, Luke.

22
00:01:24,439 --> 00:01:25,659
What a lovely introduction.

23
00:01:26,060 --> 00:01:29,980
Well, in terms of your history, we're going to talk a lot about leadership today, Sal.

24
00:01:29,980 --> 00:01:33,299
Your history in leadership is quite extraordinary,

25
00:01:33,480 --> 00:01:34,900
from the youngest possible age.

26
00:01:35,420 --> 00:01:36,400
Where did you get the drive from?

27
00:01:37,739 --> 00:01:43,980
Well, I'm really comfortable in the have-a-go mode.

28
00:01:44,519 --> 00:01:47,000
I know that probably sounds a bit simplistic,

29
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:49,319
but I've been brought up that way.

30
00:01:50,060 --> 00:01:52,180
And when you're in have-a-go mode,

31
00:01:52,540 --> 00:01:55,760
you do appreciate that there are going to be consequences,

32
00:01:56,140 --> 00:01:59,379
humiliations and embarrassments and failures, frankly.

33
00:01:59,819 --> 00:02:01,980
But if you're comfortable in the have-a-go mode,

34
00:02:02,019 --> 00:02:03,859
it means that you'll keep having a go

35
00:02:03,859 --> 00:02:06,120
and you're not daunted by those situations.

36
00:02:06,299 --> 00:02:08,340
And I think there's a lot about leadership,

37
00:02:08,500 --> 00:02:11,840
about really stepping into the unknown or the undecided

38
00:02:11,840 --> 00:02:15,439
or the opaqueness of so many situations.

39
00:02:15,439 --> 00:02:16,520
And let's face it,

40
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:21,819
it's rare that you get an easy yes, no, go, stop situation.

41
00:02:21,960 --> 00:02:27,659
It's really about managing the 49% to 51% situations

42
00:02:27,659 --> 00:02:30,520
where there are pros and cons both ways,

43
00:02:30,620 --> 00:02:33,120
but you've actually got to step into making a decision.

44
00:02:33,780 --> 00:02:35,979
And to me, that's a lot to do with leadership.

45
00:02:35,979 --> 00:02:39,919
But what's really helped me is that I'm really comfortable in having a go.

46
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:43,520
Can you give me an example, Sal, where we've gone for,

47
00:02:43,740 --> 00:02:45,860
I don't know, but I'm just going to have a go.

48
00:02:45,860 --> 00:02:45,919
Yeah.

49
00:02:46,159 --> 00:02:46,360
Hmm.

50
00:02:46,360 --> 00:02:50,740
Well, so many, as you've said, and I do get nervous, of course.

51
00:02:51,020 --> 00:02:54,919
One of the things that really stands out for me when I was younger

52
00:02:54,919 --> 00:02:58,979
was my father saying to me, nerves are the sign of a champion.

53
00:02:59,500 --> 00:03:03,080
And it's all about how you channel those nerves, that adrenaline,

54
00:03:03,560 --> 00:03:07,699
that fear into something better or more positive.

55
00:03:07,939 --> 00:03:09,960
So that was very early advice that I have.

56
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,560
And I think that that's really underpinning of being willing

57
00:03:13,560 --> 00:03:15,520
to put yourself out there and take risks.

58
00:03:15,520 --> 00:03:19,819
But even if I think about the decision to run for Lord Mayor,

59
00:03:20,039 --> 00:03:23,340
for example, which has been one of the biggest changes in my life,

60
00:03:23,379 --> 00:03:30,319
in my family's life in 2018, and it was very much that sense of passion

61
00:03:30,319 --> 00:03:33,020
and wanting to make a difference and seeing something

62
00:03:33,020 --> 00:03:35,860
that I felt I could really add some value to,

63
00:03:35,979 --> 00:03:38,680
but it was really more that I wanted to see change.

64
00:03:39,400 --> 00:03:43,139
And I had no qualifications in local government.

65
00:03:43,139 --> 00:03:45,340
I'd never really even considered local.

66
00:03:45,340 --> 00:03:47,340
I didn't consider local government seriously in many

67
00:03:47,340 --> 00:03:50,460
of the activities I'd had previously, particularly in business.

68
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:52,539
I hadn't had a lot of interactions.

69
00:03:53,180 --> 00:03:56,659
And again, I've never seriously been involved in policy development.

70
00:03:57,300 --> 00:03:59,580
Or maybe I'm talking myself out of this job at the moment.

71
00:04:00,020 --> 00:04:02,719
But there were all of these things that go through your mind,

72
00:04:02,780 --> 00:04:05,259
as well as the taking on public roles like this

73
00:04:05,259 --> 00:04:06,819
and putting yourself out there in an election.

74
00:04:06,939 --> 00:04:09,319
It is one of the scariest things I've ever done.

75
00:04:09,400 --> 00:04:10,379
It's really hard.

76
00:04:10,939 --> 00:04:15,099
And all of those things ran through my mind and my husband Andrew's mind

77
00:04:15,099 --> 00:04:15,180
and my family's mind.

78
00:04:15,180 --> 00:04:15,319
And I think that's really important.

79
00:04:15,340 --> 00:04:16,680
We like to do things as a team.

80
00:04:16,779 --> 00:04:17,560
That's always great.

81
00:04:18,160 --> 00:04:21,800
And ultimately, we made the decision staring at the ceiling

82
00:04:21,800 --> 00:04:24,339
late on a Sunday night where we just said,

83
00:04:25,019 --> 00:04:26,480
this is something we're going to do.

84
00:04:26,959 --> 00:04:30,959
And it was that even with the considerations of all the downside,

85
00:04:31,220 --> 00:04:35,120
that sense of passion and purpose really driving that decision-making

86
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:39,779
to take the risk to go into a situation that seemed quite daunting

87
00:04:39,779 --> 00:04:41,879
and scary at that time.

88
00:04:42,279 --> 00:04:45,180
But knowing that even in having a go, and this was the thing

89
00:04:45,180 --> 00:04:48,439
that unlocked it for us, even in the having a go

90
00:04:48,439 --> 00:04:51,800
and putting up a different proposition for Lord Mayor,

91
00:04:51,939 --> 00:04:56,980
somebody that was quite different, that that would make a positive impact,

92
00:04:57,620 --> 00:05:00,579
that really unlocked that decision for us and away we went.

93
00:05:00,639 --> 00:05:01,480
Yeah, awesome story.

94
00:05:01,620 --> 00:05:04,379
That's success anyway, whether the outcome is what you wanted,

95
00:05:04,459 --> 00:05:06,040
which you've been elected twice.

96
00:05:06,180 --> 00:05:10,839
No one else as a female Lord Mayor has ever been publicly elected twice.

97
00:05:10,879 --> 00:05:12,660
I just want to go back because I love what you said before,

98
00:05:12,660 --> 00:05:14,680
you know, the words from your dad.

99
00:05:14,759 --> 00:05:14,879
I went,

100
00:05:14,879 --> 00:05:17,620
the great pleasure of meeting too, Brian Capp, and what a legend.

101
00:05:17,779 --> 00:05:18,339
Talk about someone.

102
00:05:18,899 --> 00:05:22,660
I occasionally walk past him outside Kooyong and he's driven

103
00:05:22,660 --> 00:05:25,040
and I can picture him having a go.

104
00:05:25,120 --> 00:05:26,000
But nerves are for champions.

105
00:05:26,079 --> 00:05:28,100
I remember hearing the great Tony Lockett,

106
00:05:28,160 --> 00:05:29,899
who's the greatest goal kicker in the history of AFL,

107
00:05:30,040 --> 00:05:34,920
and had the pleasure or maybe displeasure of playing against him at one stage.

108
00:05:35,120 --> 00:05:36,819
And he was so nervous pre-game.

109
00:05:37,199 --> 00:05:38,939
It literally would make him so sick every game.

110
00:05:39,019 --> 00:05:41,079
I think, God, if you're that nervous,

111
00:05:41,519 --> 00:05:43,779
because you scared a lot of people out there, Tony Lockett.

112
00:05:43,779 --> 00:05:44,860
He was a fearsome.

113
00:05:44,879 --> 00:05:45,639
He was a fearsome character.

114
00:05:45,860 --> 00:05:48,079
But as you said, if you can harness that energy,

115
00:05:48,339 --> 00:05:51,639
it becomes real positive and it's a power, not a weakness in the end.

116
00:05:51,759 --> 00:05:51,920
Yeah.

117
00:05:52,139 --> 00:05:55,180
It's also very humanizing, I think,

118
00:05:55,319 --> 00:05:58,300
to realize that other people are in the same situation.

119
00:05:58,720 --> 00:06:03,480
And mostly now to help me manage my nerves,

120
00:06:04,060 --> 00:06:07,560
I do also reflect that there are many people in the audience

121
00:06:07,560 --> 00:06:10,579
that would empathize with the situation

122
00:06:10,579 --> 00:06:12,980
and would know that I'm feeling that way.

123
00:06:12,980 --> 00:06:14,579
And mostly in my life,

124
00:06:14,579 --> 00:06:16,759
I've found that people want to be supportive

125
00:06:16,759 --> 00:06:19,360
and they want to provide advice and guidance

126
00:06:19,360 --> 00:06:23,939
and they want to share those sorts of situations with you in a positive way.

127
00:06:23,939 --> 00:06:29,939
And I really lean on those thoughts and that energy

128
00:06:29,939 --> 00:06:32,399
to help me manage those fears.

129
00:06:32,959 --> 00:06:34,800
That might sound quite esoteric,

130
00:06:34,879 --> 00:06:36,399
but I literally can look at the audience

131
00:06:36,399 --> 00:06:39,680
and think a lot of people out there have been in my situation

132
00:06:39,680 --> 00:06:41,019
and they know I'll be feeling nervous

133
00:06:41,019 --> 00:06:44,560
and they will be willing me to be successful.

134
00:06:44,579 --> 00:06:47,160
I might be deluding myself, but that's what I say.

135
00:06:47,259 --> 00:06:50,160
And I really harness that energy as well.

136
00:06:50,199 --> 00:06:52,519
And when I look out at those situations

137
00:06:52,519 --> 00:06:55,699
or even if I'm standing in front of a media pack,

138
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:01,019
I really honestly do bring it back to human to human scale

139
00:07:01,019 --> 00:07:03,240
and that really helps me move forward.

140
00:07:03,540 --> 00:07:06,120
You've had so many firsts along the journey

141
00:07:06,120 --> 00:07:07,680
and glass ceiling you've smashed through.

142
00:07:07,759 --> 00:07:10,120
It's probably a few concrete ceilings really to think what you've done.

143
00:07:10,120 --> 00:07:14,399
And the first female agent general for Victoria based in London.

144
00:07:14,399 --> 00:07:18,000
And what you did in that role expanded it to other regions.

145
00:07:18,160 --> 00:07:20,360
First female board member of the famous Cullingham Football Club.

146
00:07:20,500 --> 00:07:23,399
First ever, as we said, publicly elected female Lord Mayor.

147
00:07:23,899 --> 00:07:24,639
I love what you said.

148
00:07:24,740 --> 00:07:25,439
Have a go.

149
00:07:25,600 --> 00:07:26,439
I'm going to take this on.

150
00:07:26,480 --> 00:07:29,360
I may be nervous, but there are a lot of firsts.

151
00:07:29,500 --> 00:07:30,519
I mean, when you look back,

152
00:07:30,699 --> 00:07:32,720
how challenging was it to do that so often?

153
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:38,240
Well, I think I don't consciously look for those sorts of opportunities.

154
00:07:38,399 --> 00:07:39,740
And most people would say that.

155
00:07:40,060 --> 00:07:44,060
What I'm always looking for are ways to add value

156
00:07:44,060 --> 00:07:44,100
and to be able to do that.

157
00:07:44,399 --> 00:07:45,680
And gain value.

158
00:07:46,040 --> 00:07:51,379
And I actually look for that in the people that I might employ in my teams

159
00:07:51,379 --> 00:07:52,899
or I might work with in partnership.

160
00:07:52,959 --> 00:07:55,459
Because in any sort of situation,

161
00:07:55,480 --> 00:07:59,699
you have to have a mutuality to make sure that it really binds

162
00:07:59,699 --> 00:08:02,980
and that you've got that shared purpose and goal.

163
00:08:03,060 --> 00:08:05,420
There has to be a value on both sides.

164
00:08:05,620 --> 00:08:10,540
So for me, I'm always looking at what have I already learnt or done

165
00:08:10,540 --> 00:08:13,199
and that experience that I can feel confident

166
00:08:13,199 --> 00:08:14,300
that it's going to make a difference.

167
00:08:14,300 --> 00:08:15,860
to a role I'm going into.

168
00:08:16,259 --> 00:08:19,040
But also what's new about that that really challenges me

169
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:21,139
and means that I'm still learning and developing.

170
00:08:21,740 --> 00:08:23,759
And I guess that's part of feeling comfortable

171
00:08:23,759 --> 00:08:27,279
in being outside your comfort zone because I welcome that.

172
00:08:27,920 --> 00:08:30,300
And when it comes to those firsts,

173
00:08:30,959 --> 00:08:35,779
every single one of those times has been that as the underlying element.

174
00:08:36,039 --> 00:08:39,620
And then I also look for not just the one step forward,

175
00:08:39,679 --> 00:08:42,279
but the 10 steps forward, whether that's for me personally,

176
00:08:42,279 --> 00:08:43,960
whether that's for the organisation,

177
00:08:43,960 --> 00:08:46,919
or that's for the role, or in some cases it's been,

178
00:08:47,120 --> 00:08:49,320
what does it mean for women in leadership as well?

179
00:08:49,899 --> 00:08:52,559
And where you can add those dimensions in,

180
00:08:52,679 --> 00:08:54,500
then that's extra special.

181
00:08:55,039 --> 00:08:58,720
But a big part of it is, firstly, I've had lots of bumps

182
00:08:58,720 --> 00:09:01,419
against the ceiling where it's hurt my head more

183
00:09:01,419 --> 00:09:02,980
than I've made much progress.

184
00:09:03,940 --> 00:09:07,940
And two, I know that in taking on those roles,

185
00:09:08,120 --> 00:09:10,659
there are risks and I'm really comfortable with,

186
00:09:11,279 --> 00:09:13,740
I wouldn't say failing, nobody sets out to fail,

187
00:09:13,740 --> 00:09:17,659
but if I need to be vulnerable in those times to say

188
00:09:17,659 --> 00:09:19,899
that I've never done this before, or this is new,

189
00:09:19,960 --> 00:09:22,860
or it's new for the organisation, or it's a difficult environment,

190
00:09:23,019 --> 00:09:25,159
I'm really comfortable to call those things out.

191
00:09:25,679 --> 00:09:29,200
And again, I think it makes it also easier for the people

192
00:09:29,200 --> 00:09:33,080
around you to respond as well because when you go in as the first,

193
00:09:33,159 --> 00:09:35,399
so I remember that first Collingwood board meeting

194
00:09:35,399 --> 00:09:40,220
in the old Victoria Park social club upstairs in the legendary ballroom

195
00:09:40,220 --> 00:09:42,899
that has a fist punch through one of the walls

196
00:09:42,899 --> 00:09:47,700
and cracks in the glass doors and carpet that your feet stick to

197
00:09:47,700 --> 00:09:50,059
on the way through, you know, the bar area.

198
00:09:50,519 --> 00:09:55,279
And I remember how nervous our fellow board members were as well.

199
00:09:55,279 --> 00:09:56,360
Ed, very welcoming.

200
00:09:56,799 --> 00:10:00,600
But I was new into that culture and also being the first female,

201
00:10:00,720 --> 00:10:02,700
that was something completely different,

202
00:10:02,960 --> 00:10:08,980
not just somebody that was from outside the little group there.

203
00:10:09,100 --> 00:10:12,720
So I remember so distinctly that one

204
00:10:12,720 --> 00:10:17,000
of the things that was necessary to do was make the other board members

205
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:20,940
feel comfortable with me being there and so really putting it out there

206
00:10:20,940 --> 00:10:25,460
that there were many things I didn't know and I was keen to learn,

207
00:10:25,539 --> 00:10:28,139
but here are the things that I thought I was pretty good at

208
00:10:28,139 --> 00:10:31,159
and where I could add value and that immediately gave them a sense

209
00:10:31,159 --> 00:10:34,240
of where I was going to play even if that was initially

210
00:10:34,240 --> 00:10:37,179
and where my focus areas were going to be

211
00:10:37,179 --> 00:10:39,259
and we started up a bit of a common language.

212
00:10:39,919 --> 00:10:42,559
I remember Kevin Rose saying that he'd purposefully,

213
00:10:42,720 --> 00:10:46,860
reduce the amount of F words he said in the meeting as a result,

214
00:10:46,980 --> 00:10:48,320
all those sorts of fun things.

215
00:10:48,720 --> 00:10:53,840
But you do need to find that equilibrium and being first should be

216
00:10:53,840 --> 00:10:58,179
as good an experience for everybody around you as it is for you,

217
00:10:58,320 --> 00:11:02,799
particularly when you know you're going into something that's new

218
00:11:02,799 --> 00:11:07,659
or uncertain or potentially difficult and really building that rapport

219
00:11:07,659 --> 00:11:09,600
so people can work together is important.

220
00:11:09,899 --> 00:11:11,200
Yeah, and picking up on what you said,

221
00:11:11,379 --> 00:11:12,679
so we're talking a lot about,

222
00:11:12,720 --> 00:11:15,740
empowering leadership and I love what you said,

223
00:11:15,879 --> 00:11:17,659
it's a value add both ways.

224
00:11:17,759 --> 00:11:20,159
So if you're employing someone in your Lord Mayor's office

225
00:11:20,159 --> 00:11:23,639
or likewise if it's someone who's supporting you on the campaign,

226
00:11:24,200 --> 00:11:27,840
there's got to be a value both ways and I suppose that's something

227
00:11:27,840 --> 00:11:30,679
that we're really passionate about is there is a bit of a shift now

228
00:11:30,679 --> 00:11:32,259
that people are looking to that.

229
00:11:32,360 --> 00:11:36,000
It's not just there's a hierarchy and the old school leadership

230
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:37,220
and you would have come up through that with,

231
00:11:37,799 --> 00:11:41,399
I often speak about the big corner office and you know what,

232
00:11:41,500 --> 00:11:42,600
you get your set tasks.

233
00:11:42,720 --> 00:11:43,559
When you haven't got a voice,

234
00:11:43,879 --> 00:11:46,240
do you think that that is the way forward now

235
00:11:46,240 --> 00:11:48,220
where it generally has to be a collaboration

236
00:11:48,220 --> 00:11:49,139
with the people you work with?

237
00:11:49,259 --> 00:11:50,080
How good is that?

238
00:11:50,279 --> 00:11:50,419
Yeah.

239
00:11:50,419 --> 00:11:53,279
I mean, what were we even thinking in the old days?

240
00:11:53,460 --> 00:11:57,259
I remember as a young lawyer going to a meeting

241
00:11:57,259 --> 00:11:59,539
with a senior partner, very senior,

242
00:11:59,659 --> 00:12:01,480
and it wasn't I lucky to be in that meeting

243
00:12:01,480 --> 00:12:03,080
and I'd been asked to prepare for it.

244
00:12:03,179 --> 00:12:07,419
So being diligent, I did that and I read up all the regulations

245
00:12:07,419 --> 00:12:10,460
and I was ready and during the course of that meeting,

246
00:12:10,600 --> 00:12:11,820
the client asked a question.

247
00:12:12,720 --> 00:12:14,539
And because I'd done all that preparation,

248
00:12:14,940 --> 00:12:17,139
I stepped into the conversation at that point

249
00:12:17,139 --> 00:12:20,240
and I gave an opinion based on my research.

