00:12:48,179 --> 00:12:51,960
And I think to the circumstances now where I can play a really big role

263
00:12:51,960 --> 00:12:55,460
in this and that is valuing the input of other people

264
00:12:55,460 --> 00:12:58,700
and knowing that whether it's people with less experience,

265
00:12:58,820 --> 00:13:01,639
so they're bringing new eyes, people with more experience,

266
00:13:01,759 --> 00:13:03,080
or people with different perspectives,

267
00:13:03,679 --> 00:13:07,820
that that diversity of thinking actually gives you a better result,

268
00:13:08,039 --> 00:13:11,440
whether it's internally or externally in your organisation,

269
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:12,700
to really embrace that.

270
00:13:12,700 --> 00:13:14,940
Embrace that is powerful.

271
00:13:15,779 --> 00:13:17,100
And it does mean, of course,

272
00:13:17,200 --> 00:13:20,980
that it adds a complexity to your decision-making and your processes.

273
00:13:21,440 --> 00:13:25,700
But from my perspective, that investment has been paid back in spades.

274
00:13:26,259 --> 00:13:28,539
And so it is the new way of going forward.

275
00:13:28,639 --> 00:13:30,179
It's a new way of leading.

276
00:13:30,600 --> 00:13:33,279
It does have some challenges to it, but they're absolutely worthwhile.

277
00:13:33,899 --> 00:13:35,019
How old were you when that happened?

278
00:13:35,360 --> 00:13:36,559
Oh, 22.

279
00:13:37,320 --> 00:13:39,980
So how do you pick yourself up from that?

280
00:13:40,100 --> 00:13:41,120
What did you do next?

281
00:13:41,120 --> 00:13:41,820
Well, exactly.

282
00:13:41,820 --> 00:13:46,720
And there were more of those situations as a young lawyer

283
00:13:46,720 --> 00:13:50,379
in that very hierarchical world, particularly, I've got to say,

284
00:13:50,460 --> 00:13:55,059
particularly as a female, than now.

285
00:13:55,340 --> 00:13:59,179
And another great lesson from my parents was,

286
00:13:59,580 --> 00:14:02,139
it's an old adage, what doesn't kill you makes you stronger.

