00:24:19,279 --> 00:24:22,440
that usually behind the scenes there's an incredible amount of effort

500
00:24:22,440 --> 00:24:27,940
and emotion and dedication and patience and commitment that's gone

501
00:24:27,940 --> 00:24:29,640
into this and it has.

502
00:24:29,720 --> 00:24:32,799
It's been a real juggle and there are some really big decisions

503
00:24:32,799 --> 00:24:37,059
that you make along the way and I think that's another reflection

504
00:24:37,059 --> 00:24:37,599
for me.

505
00:24:37,720 --> 00:24:40,779
There have been times when I've really been tormented

506
00:24:40,779 --> 00:24:44,220
about decisions because it's that juggle and that balance

507
00:24:44,220 --> 00:24:48,680
and particularly when you've got children and you want to be able

508
00:24:48,680 --> 00:24:52,339
to spend really great quality time with the kids but you want

509
00:24:52,339 --> 00:24:55,220
to be able to pursue a career as well.

510
00:24:55,220 --> 00:25:01,500
Those sorts of difficult balance decisions come up all of the time

511
00:25:01,500 --> 00:25:07,559
and when I look back, I really feel that where we've gone forward on the basis,

512
00:25:07,720 --> 00:25:12,579
of things that are value-based, that are what's most important to us,

513
00:25:12,640 --> 00:25:17,619
where we've had discussions, Andrew and I, about really what those priorities

514
00:25:17,619 --> 00:25:22,980
are at the end of the day, what makes us happy, what brings us joy

515
00:25:22,980 --> 00:25:28,200
and making sure we have that focus on relationships and family,

516
00:25:28,539 --> 00:25:30,400
whether it's family or it's friends as well.

517
00:25:30,599 --> 00:25:33,880
When it comes down to it, they need to be the priority

518
00:25:33,880 --> 00:25:37,279
because they're going to be the most lasting, the most fulfilling,

519
00:25:37,279 --> 00:25:43,000
the most satisfying and I think we've managed that balance pretty well

520
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:46,680
but there have been some really stressful times when you're considering

521
00:25:46,680 --> 00:25:49,240
what's in front of you and what's the best way forward.

522
00:25:57,059 --> 00:26:01,039
Changing tax cell for a little bit, there's so many areas to go with you

523
00:26:01,039 --> 00:26:05,240
but I'm interested in now you're in this incredible leadership role,

524
00:26:05,839 --> 00:26:08,880
high profile in Melbourne, there's so much that comes your way

525
00:26:08,880 --> 00:26:12,819
but then you've got this element of social media that everyone's got

526
00:26:12,819 --> 00:26:13,660
to deal with now too.

527
00:26:13,680 --> 00:26:15,619
And to me, it's a disgrace.

528
00:26:15,819 --> 00:26:20,680
Female leaders in particular seem to get absolutely attacked on that basis.

529
00:26:21,460 --> 00:26:23,420
I mean, a lot of people are dealing that every day.

530
00:26:23,539 --> 00:26:26,359
Teenage kids, most people have got that.

531
00:26:26,440 --> 00:26:27,500
How do you cope with that?

532
00:26:28,599 --> 00:26:33,900
It's a really good question because being in public roles as well,

533
00:26:34,700 --> 00:26:36,019
so there are two elements here.

534
00:26:36,839 --> 00:26:42,819
Public roles seem to mean that there are no rules even of normal civility

535
00:26:42,819 --> 00:26:43,579
that apply.

536
00:26:43,680 --> 00:26:43,940
Yeah.

537
00:26:44,500 --> 00:26:46,019
To people in public roles.

538
00:26:46,200 --> 00:26:50,880
I've found that really confronting and also social media, as you know,

539
00:26:51,119 --> 00:26:54,099
just seems to give permission for people to say anything they want to

540
00:26:54,099 --> 00:26:58,420
with absolutely no consequences and that's really disappointing

541
00:26:58,420 --> 00:27:02,119
and more of us need to stand up to say that's unacceptable

542
00:27:02,119 --> 00:27:06,579
and I see more of that sort of conversation and discussion coming through

543
00:27:06,579 --> 00:27:08,460
as we go forward.

544
00:27:09,180 --> 00:27:11,640
Of course, you have to have a very thick skin.

545
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:13,359
There's no doubt about that.

546
00:27:13,359 --> 00:27:17,160
And there are times still, and that's where I lean on my team a lot as well,

547
00:27:17,279 --> 00:27:22,680
of sanity checking and support in those moments.

548
00:27:22,980 --> 00:27:27,160
But it does also, and I think the last 12 months have particularly highlighted

549
00:27:27,160 --> 00:27:33,619
this for me, you have to have a resolve if you want to be a leader

550
00:27:33,619 --> 00:27:37,920
and if you want to be involved in these sorts of discussions and debates

551
00:27:37,920 --> 00:27:40,619
and let's face it, there are highlights and there are lowlights

552
00:27:40,619 --> 00:27:43,299
and if you want to be involved in important issues,

553
00:27:43,359 --> 00:27:49,220
and progress in our community, then you really have to be willing

554
00:27:49,220 --> 00:27:55,279
to have that resolve to keep going even when it feels like everybody

555
00:27:55,279 --> 00:27:59,460
around you is telling you that it's wrong or you're doing a bad job,

556
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:03,039
criticising, undermining, attacking.

557
00:28:03,859 --> 00:28:07,900
You have to have that centre in yourself of that resolve.

558
00:28:08,079 --> 00:28:11,519
Part of that is being willing to admit if you've made a mistake.

559
00:28:11,519 --> 00:28:13,319
I think that's really important.

560
00:28:13,359 --> 00:28:16,359
And part of leadership and having the resolve to do that.

561
00:28:16,460 --> 00:28:20,539
I can tell you I've had to do that and it's tough,

562
00:28:21,059 --> 00:28:24,000
but if you think it's the right thing to do, you must do it.

563
00:28:24,059 --> 00:28:26,220
And same if you think something's the right thing to do

564
00:28:26,220 --> 00:28:29,079
and everybody's telling you it's wrong, then just keep going

565
00:28:29,079 --> 00:28:32,900
because even in doing it, you're making a difference

566
00:28:32,900 --> 00:28:35,119
no matter what the ultimate outcome is.

567
00:28:35,960 --> 00:28:38,680
And so I've become much more focused on that.

568
00:28:38,680 --> 00:28:41,859
But I will say I am a team player

569
00:28:41,859 --> 00:28:46,539
and I think building a team around you

570
00:28:46,539 --> 00:28:48,200
who can have different views to you

571
00:28:48,200 --> 00:28:50,960
but will absolutely stand behind you when needed

572
00:28:50,960 --> 00:28:53,000
and that's both in your personal life

573
00:28:53,000 --> 00:28:56,980
and in professional life is key and absolutely necessary.

574
00:28:57,160 --> 00:29:01,059
I think what you said about owning the mistake that is yours

575
00:29:01,059 --> 00:29:04,700
feels a bit like a lost start in 2021 to me

576
00:29:04,700 --> 00:29:06,960
and particularly I can't understand

577
00:29:06,960 --> 00:29:09,539
and walk in your shoes in political life now,

578
00:29:09,539 --> 00:29:10,880
but there seems to be,

579
00:29:10,880 --> 00:29:13,279
there seems to be that advisors are saying

580
00:29:13,279 --> 00:29:15,680
whatever you do, don't accept responsibility.

581
00:29:16,140 --> 00:29:18,700
Whereas to me, it's the most human thing to do, isn't it?

582
00:29:18,720 --> 00:29:21,960
A disarming thing to do is, and clearly part of your makeup.

583
00:29:22,099 --> 00:29:23,839
Is that going to always stay with you?

584
00:29:24,700 --> 00:29:25,140
Absolutely.

585
00:29:26,460 --> 00:29:29,240
And I think it's a testament to you, Luke, as well.

586
00:29:29,299 --> 00:29:32,440
And I do look for other people and leaders that,

587
00:29:33,059 --> 00:29:34,740
to me, that's a standout characteristic.

588
00:29:34,980 --> 00:29:36,000
It's a differentiator.

589
00:29:36,900 --> 00:29:40,859
And I like to work with people.

590
00:29:40,880 --> 00:29:41,819
I like to work with people like that

591
00:29:41,819 --> 00:29:44,519
and learn from people who have that approach.

592
00:29:45,259 --> 00:29:47,259
It's much more relatable.

593
00:29:48,019 --> 00:29:51,220
I think it really drives much more empathy as well

594
00:29:51,220 --> 00:29:53,640
and understanding of what you're going through.

595
00:29:53,980 --> 00:29:56,599
And it's actually one of the toughest things you can do.

596
00:29:56,700 --> 00:29:57,720
So if you do, do it.

597
00:29:58,160 --> 00:30:01,220
But it also creates the environment for other people to do it.

598
00:30:01,299 --> 00:30:03,200
Now, what we find in culture so much

599
00:30:03,200 --> 00:30:07,240
is that deflection or avoidance, distraction or cover-up

600
00:30:07,240 --> 00:30:09,619
because people don't want to admit mistakes.

601
00:30:09,619 --> 00:30:10,819
If that's the sort of culture,

602
00:30:10,880 --> 00:30:13,859
you have danger, danger, warning, warning.

603
00:30:14,440 --> 00:30:17,240
Much better to have a culture where people feel comfortable

604
00:30:17,240 --> 00:30:20,279
to call out mistakes or to say sorry

605
00:30:20,279 --> 00:30:24,700
or to identify issues and be open to that as well

606
00:30:24,700 --> 00:30:26,680
so that you can keep moving forward.

607
00:30:26,720 --> 00:30:28,220
Because let's face it, we all do it.

608
00:30:28,299 --> 00:30:30,279
It happens every day and it has to.

609
00:30:30,740 --> 00:30:34,279
In the pace and complexity of life these days,

610
00:30:34,460 --> 00:30:36,740
we know that these things are going to happen.

611
00:30:36,740 --> 00:30:40,859
So the sooner you fail and the more open,

612
00:30:40,859 --> 00:30:45,119
you are to mistakes and to moving forward from that,

613
00:30:45,339 --> 00:30:47,900
the more effective you can be.

614
00:30:48,460 --> 00:30:51,140
And I remember actually just back to the campaign

615
00:30:51,140 --> 00:30:53,720
when we set up the first campaign in 2018,

616
00:30:53,720 --> 00:30:56,819
had no idea what we were doing, Andrew and I,

617
00:30:57,279 --> 00:30:59,039
which we worked out in about five minutes.

618
00:30:59,200 --> 00:31:02,319
We set up a team around us to support us

619
00:31:02,319 --> 00:31:04,160
and frankly lead in many ways.

620
00:31:04,400 --> 00:31:06,299
And one of the first things I said is,

621
00:31:06,619 --> 00:31:08,759
please know I am going to make a lot of mistakes

622
00:31:08,759 --> 00:31:10,420
because I've never done this before.

623
00:31:10,859 --> 00:31:13,079
And I need you to point those out to me

624
00:31:13,079 --> 00:31:15,880
as quickly as possible so that we can respond to them

625
00:31:15,880 --> 00:31:18,299
and deal with them and move on.

626
00:31:19,220 --> 00:31:22,500
And a wonderful person, Nicole,

627
00:31:22,599 --> 00:31:23,900
who was our campaign manager,

628
00:31:23,900 --> 00:31:24,740
looked at me and said,

629
00:31:24,799 --> 00:31:26,539
that's the most brilliant thing you could have said

630
00:31:26,539 --> 00:31:28,200
because I'll make mistakes too,

631
00:31:28,240 --> 00:31:29,779
even though I've done this many times

632
00:31:29,779 --> 00:31:31,799
and so will other team members.

633
00:31:31,799 --> 00:31:35,700
And so it created a very constructive culture,

634
00:31:35,859 --> 00:31:37,319
which we had to form instantly

635
00:31:37,319 --> 00:31:39,099
because we only had three months

636
00:31:39,099 --> 00:31:40,759
to pull the whole thing together.

637
00:31:40,859 --> 00:31:45,059
And it was really set a pace and a momentum

638
00:31:45,059 --> 00:31:46,619
to what we could achieve as a team

639
00:31:46,619 --> 00:31:49,140
because that was one of our underlying principles.

640
00:31:49,539 --> 00:31:51,319
Yeah, I'm really conscious, Bec and I,

641
00:31:51,579 --> 00:31:52,720
parenting-wise as well,

642
00:31:52,859 --> 00:31:53,720
is to just occasionally,

643
00:31:54,039 --> 00:31:55,759
more than occasionally as it turns out,

644
00:31:55,859 --> 00:31:57,500
and go, hey, geez, I got that wrong.

645
00:31:57,960 --> 00:32:00,359
And it's pretty disarming for the kids to hear that as well,

646
00:32:00,539 --> 00:32:01,599
to look at you and go,

647
00:32:02,160 --> 00:32:03,980
yeah, I think I maybe pulled the wrong rein there

648
00:32:03,980 --> 00:32:05,880
and maybe lost it a little bit on that occasion.

649
00:32:05,980 --> 00:32:08,380
And you're fine, you can then move forward

650
00:32:08,380 --> 00:32:10,460
and allow them to have conversations as well,

651
00:32:10,859 --> 00:32:11,539
being great.

652
00:32:11,619 --> 00:32:13,200
So you don't achieve what you do

653
00:32:13,200 --> 00:32:14,339
and have the family balance,

654
00:32:14,740 --> 00:32:17,059
I'm assuming, without some pretty good rituals

655
00:32:17,059 --> 00:32:18,420
and routines and habits.

656
00:32:18,500 --> 00:32:20,740
Is there anything you can share with us on that front?

657
00:32:21,160 --> 00:32:22,279
What a good question.

658
00:32:22,480 --> 00:32:22,839
Wow.

659
00:32:24,380 --> 00:32:26,799
Routines and habits, very good.

660
00:32:27,359 --> 00:32:28,440
I like to,

661
00:32:29,059 --> 00:32:31,480
I haven't, nobody's asked me that for ages, Luke,

662
00:32:31,559 --> 00:32:32,359
so good one.

663
00:32:33,420 --> 00:32:35,599
I try to be very organised.

664
00:32:35,859 --> 00:32:37,599
So in the chaos of life,

665
00:32:37,599 --> 00:32:40,279
I do really like to have a diary

666
00:32:40,279 --> 00:32:40,700
that's,

667
00:32:40,700 --> 00:32:42,119
that's been well thought through

668
00:32:42,119 --> 00:32:43,900
in terms of what's on for the day.

669
00:32:44,240 --> 00:32:47,599
And I rely on other people to help me completely with that.

670
00:32:47,779 --> 00:32:49,500
I like to really stick to time.

671
00:32:49,700 --> 00:32:52,079
I value your time, you value my time.

672
00:32:52,220 --> 00:32:54,920
So I really like to do that.

673
00:32:55,099 --> 00:32:57,960
I find that the more organised you can be

674
00:32:57,960 --> 00:32:59,720
on the things that you can control,

675
00:32:59,720 --> 00:33:02,279
the more receptive and agile you can be

676
00:33:02,279 --> 00:33:04,339
to the things that are beyond your control.

677
00:33:04,480 --> 00:33:07,920
So we really focus on those elements of our lives

678
00:33:07,920 --> 00:33:10,220
that we can control personally and professionally.

679
00:33:10,700 --> 00:33:12,940
And then that sets us up for,

680
00:33:13,059 --> 00:33:15,660
for the unexpected and unpredictable things

681
00:33:15,660 --> 00:33:17,619
that happen in life.

682
00:33:18,339 --> 00:33:22,440
We always have people that can catch the balls

683
00:33:22,440 --> 00:33:23,980
that we might have missed.

684
00:33:24,480 --> 00:33:26,680
And that's been absolutely key,

685
00:33:26,819 --> 00:33:29,220
particularly for juggling family and profession.

686
00:33:29,420 --> 00:33:31,319
So I have been so lucky with family,

687
00:33:32,079 --> 00:33:33,819
my parents-in-law, my parents,

688
00:33:34,359 --> 00:33:36,059
sisters-in-law particularly,

689
00:33:36,539 --> 00:33:39,400
and my siblings to know that there are people

690
00:33:39,400 --> 00:33:40,279
that can catch the balls.

691
00:33:40,279 --> 00:33:40,319
And I think that's a really good thing.

692
00:33:40,319 --> 00:33:40,400
And I think that's a really good thing.

693
00:33:40,400 --> 00:33:40,539
And I think that's a really good thing.

694
00:33:40,539 --> 00:33:40,680
And I think that's a really good thing.

695
00:33:40,680 --> 00:33:42,599
And even in primary school,

696
00:33:42,680 --> 00:33:44,779
when I was really working so hard

697
00:33:44,779 --> 00:33:47,579
to get that career moving to the next level,

698
00:33:47,700 --> 00:33:49,539
to know that I could rely on other mums,

699
00:33:49,859 --> 00:33:52,279
I was straight out to other mums to say,

700
00:33:52,460 --> 00:33:53,940
hey, I'm going to need your help.

701
00:33:54,259 --> 00:33:56,079
And the great thing when I said that,

702
00:33:56,519 --> 00:33:58,759
and the perfect one was first day of school

703
00:33:58,759 --> 00:34:01,660
for young Will, we dropped him off in the morning

704
00:34:01,660 --> 00:34:05,700
and all organised to pick him up at the gate at 3.15.

705
00:34:05,940 --> 00:34:08,800
But I got the call at 12.15 from the school

706
00:34:08,800 --> 00:34:10,519
to say, your son is going to be in school

707
00:34:10,519 --> 00:34:11,599
and your son, Will's here.

708
00:34:11,699 --> 00:34:14,599
He's the only child still here.

709
00:34:14,719 --> 00:34:15,739
And I said, what do you mean?

710
00:34:15,780 --> 00:34:17,880
And they said, the first day is a half day.

711
00:34:19,139 --> 00:34:21,380
So I completely dropped the ball

712
00:34:21,380 --> 00:34:24,420
and knowing that somebody could be there

713
00:34:24,420 --> 00:34:26,420
to help in those urgent situations.

714
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:28,679
You've got to know, and it's the same in your team.

715
00:34:28,840 --> 00:34:31,460
You've just got to know that you've got each other's back

716
00:34:31,460 --> 00:34:33,440
to be able to step into those situations.

717
00:34:34,059 --> 00:34:37,099
But the routines is very much around feeling organised

718
00:34:37,099 --> 00:34:38,760
on the things that you can control.

719
00:34:39,280 --> 00:34:40,099
We've been talking,

720
00:34:40,519 --> 00:34:41,940
a lot about in the work I've been doing

721
00:34:41,940 --> 00:34:43,719
about the dimensions of what makes a great leader.

722
00:34:43,860 --> 00:34:46,280
So what does self-leadership mean to you?

723
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:51,420
Self-leadership means accountability.

724
00:34:52,380 --> 00:34:54,500
And I mean that in a very positive way.

725
00:34:55,159 --> 00:34:58,239
Another word that a lot of people don't necessarily like,

726
00:34:58,300 --> 00:34:59,280
but is discipline.

727
00:35:00,280 --> 00:35:02,599
And I really like to have discipline.

728
00:35:03,639 --> 00:35:06,659
Having said that, and maybe it really plays

729
00:35:06,659 --> 00:35:09,079
on the discussion we've just had,

730
00:35:09,079 --> 00:35:11,380
is that I like to be spontaneous.

731
00:35:11,820 --> 00:35:14,960
I like to be a little bit crazy at times.

732
00:35:15,119 --> 00:35:16,400
Hard to believe, Luke, I know.

733
00:35:16,659 --> 00:35:19,420
I like to be a little bit naughty,

734
00:35:19,840 --> 00:35:21,500
whatever naughty is for me.

735
00:35:21,860 --> 00:35:25,159
And you've got to allow yourself those moments

736
00:35:25,159 --> 00:35:28,420
to let off steam and be yourself.

737
00:35:28,699 --> 00:35:31,239
And so that's important for me.

738
00:35:31,599 --> 00:35:35,639
To me, that comes back to the maybe overused term,

739
00:35:35,739 --> 00:35:36,900
but it is about authenticity.

740
00:35:37,460 --> 00:35:39,039
If you are,

741
00:35:39,039 --> 00:35:41,019
not being true to yourself,

742
00:35:41,760 --> 00:35:43,280
and in doing that,

743
00:35:43,500 --> 00:35:46,460
allowing other people to see the true you,

744
00:35:47,320 --> 00:35:50,099
then not only letting yourself down,

745
00:35:50,139 --> 00:35:52,460
because who wants to live a life with the stress

746
00:35:52,460 --> 00:35:54,639
of trying to be something that you're not,

747
00:35:55,239 --> 00:35:59,019
but you are letting everyone down around you.

748
00:35:59,619 --> 00:36:02,460
And the richness of life experiences

749
00:36:02,460 --> 00:36:05,019
comes from being open to that.

750
00:36:05,119 --> 00:36:06,539
So being vulnerable.

751
00:36:06,539 --> 00:36:08,920
To me, vulnerability is powerful,

752
00:36:09,039 --> 00:36:11,940
and to being completely authentic.

753
00:36:12,860 --> 00:36:16,300
And that means that you can have failures and humiliations,

